text.text: We are visiting Norfolk for a long weekend and made a day trip to Cromer, before we arrived I had seen this Wonderful gem shop online, and showed my daughter. I must confess I know very little about geology but I have a 8 year old daughter who has a growing interest in rocks and crystals so we were looking forward to visiting.  Our trip did not disappoint, talking as a layman, if you cannot find what you want in here then it’s probably doesn’t exist. My daughter is very shy and we were warmly welcomed by the lady serving who was clearly very knowledgeable and passionate about the items in the shop. My daughter who is usually very indecisive found what she liked and was very pleased with her purchases, and states she gives the shop 10/10.

editorialSummary.text: Disney retail chain featuring official character toys, clothes, collectibles & more.

text.text:
I happened to walk past at the Oxford Street Disney Store bang on opening time, and decided to explore the magic within before the crowd floods the place. Just stepping through the doors into the empty but pristine store felt special, like I had a theme park to myself!

Feeling like a kid set loose in a candy store, marveling at the sheer variety spread over three floors. Every Disney character and movie seemed represented in cuddly toys, clothing, mugs - you name it! Upstairs was a haven for big kids like me, the Marvel and Star Wars section calling my name. I resisted the temptation to pose with the lightsabers - after all, the staff still had work to do!

With the store not yet open properly, I didn't make any purchases. But I could see the magic sparkling on the shelves, from exclusive London souvenirs to timeless Disney classics.

Early morning is the perfect time to soak up the atmosphere in the last Disney Store standing in England. It was a magical start to the day!

text.text:
Russell Ackermann-Callow
I have been looking for a wall clock for some time and I stumbled on The London Timepiece via a couple of third party selling platforms. Based on this I decided to get in touch and then visited Russell Ackermann-Callow's premises at his suggestion. Following up on his prompt email communications he was charming and helpful in person and has an obvious deep knowledge/keen interest in 20th century wall clocks. It was fascinating to hear Russell talk about his work and I came away with a purchase which I am very satisfied with.  I would therefore highly recommend Russell Ackermann-Callow to anyone with a leaning towards acquiring an 'industrial style' wall clock or even a wall timepiece of a more traditional variety.

text.text:
I've bought several sets of dice from DnDice in the past, both mystery sets and sets selected to match my characters.  The quality of every set has been wonderful, and the magical item/potion cards received with each one have been a fun little bonus which I've implemented into my games as often as possible.
The only reason I give 4 stars instead of 5 is because there has been one occasion where I ordered a specific set of dice, and the wrong set was sent in its place.  Not a major issue in itself, but after trying to make contact through the website's contact form, the email address provided on the invoice, and through the DnDice Etsy page, I received no replies, forcing me to get an intervention from Paypal.
I will absolutely still be buying from DnDice in the future as I utterly love their dice, but I'm now aware that ordering issues can be problematic.

A quaint independent stationery shop doesn't quite cut it from a description of this hidden gem of a place. I think it's Japanese inspired place with wonderful notebooks, paper kens and an amazing array of ink and waxes.

It's always worth popping in if there are things that you may need to get such as the present or something different to write on or with. They have some difficult to find inks in here and even an array of fountain pens if you're feeling in that old school mood.

I would say it's always worth popping in if you're in the area of course supporting this independent business.

A top-notch stationery store- one of my favorite little shops in the area to peruse. They always have something that catches my eye (who knew that I needed metallic watercolors? I didn’t, until I stopped in one day).

They have an excellent selection of notebooks with good quality paper, lots of little desk items, and good quality pens. They also offer the best scissors you didn’t know you needed, as well as Japanese watercolors, and a few bits of local pottery.

Definitely worth a look, especially if you enjoy good paper and pens!
